            "answer_text": "They were as familiar with Nestorian theology as any other large group of people was familiar with their own. The Nestorians were dyophysites. They believed, like the Orthodox, that Christ had both a human and a divine nature, but they disagreed on the relationship. Whereas the Orthodox held that they were united, the Nestorians believed that they were separate within the body of Christ. That is, the divine Son of God occupied but was not part of the human Jesus. ",
